    <div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='2594#1160427291'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2006-10-09T20:54:51+00:00">Oct 9, 2006 08:54 PM UTC</time> by <b>Tim Silvers</b><a class="anchor" name="1160427291">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>From&#58; 	  kramer@....
Subject&#58; 	This report was filed with CIAC on October 7 and is provided for your information
Date&#58; 	October 9, 2006 4&#58;40&#58;04 PM EDT
To&#58; 	  security@....
Cc&#58; 	  DLOlson@....

On 5/25/06 s00613-en1.nersc.gov, a login in node for the Seaborg SP
cluster, was root compromised after having a user account compromised.
The initial user account compromise is suspected to be due to the user
credential theft.  The cause of the privileged escalation to root was
identified as a previously unknown vulnerability in the AIX system
software - specifically a diagnostics and maintenance system program.
This attack was documented in CIAC Ticket# 524827 and the vulnerability
was corrected following IBM approved procedures.  The other systems at
NERSC were inventoried and judged free of any compromise.

On 10/05/06 during normal system administrative activities on the same
node - s00613-en1.nersc.gov - a file was discovered in /var/opt/free
which contained a list of user id&#39;s, passwords and destination hosts
collected from users on the node who logged into other systems.  As a
response to this new information, NERSC discontinued interactive logins
to the Seaborg system and began gathering account information. Batch
jobs continued to process (there is sufficient backlog to for the system
to be fully busy for several days).

Upon closer examination, it was determined that the symbolic link for
ssh was replaced with an actual binary in order to capture the account
information.  Approximately 110 users had information connected. At 1 pm
on 10/06/06 it was determined that there was sufficient uncertainty
about the state of Seaborg to wanted a re-installation on all nodes from
a known good state before March. Further investigation continued and
we also discovered a rogue suid file located under /var/perf (&#39;prof&#39;)
which appears to be a copy of ksh.  All other systems at NERSC were
inventoried, as well as intrusion detection logs reviewed.  No other
systems showed signs of compromise, and have been returned to full service.
<div id='show_501125416' class=''><button class="btn">Show More</button></div><div class='detail hidden' id='detail_501125416'>
Standard system monitoring, in this case using cfengine, did not detect
the replaced sshd file because the binary that the symbolic link was
pointing to was replaced, not modified.  Hence, cfengine did not detect
the change.  The problem is being corrected.

Currently any user identified by the /var/opt/free list will have to
call in to get a new password after going through an identification
protocol well as having all authentication keys removed from all NERSC
systems.  In addition, both the users and the destination institution
have been notified about the potential credential theft.  Any other users
who logged into the system from May 15 till today will have to call in
to receive a new password as well.

The entire Seaborg system will be re-built in order to ensure that there
are no further problems.  This is expected to take at least 7 days.
During this period all other systems at NERSC will remain in full operation.

Bill Kramer
NERSC
510-486-7577
